        <div class="chart-placeholder">
          <img src="pastel.png" alt="Sleep Disorder Distribution">
        </div>
        <p class="chart-description">This chart shows the percentage of users affected by different types of sleep disorders such as insomnia and sleep apnea.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="chart-container">
        <div class="chart-title">Physical Activity vs Sleep Quality</div>
        <div class="chart-placeholder">
          <img src="physical_activity_vs_sleep_quality.png" alt="Activity vs Sleep Quality">
        </div>
        <p class="chart-description">People who engage in more physical activity tend to report higher sleep quality, with a clear positive trend.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="chart-container">
        <div class="chart-title">Sleep Duration Distribution</div>
        <div class="chart-placeholder">
          <img src="distribuciondehoras.png" alt="Sleep Duration Distribution">
        </div>
        <p class="chart-description">The majority of participants sleep between 6 and 8 hours, with fewer reporting either very short or long durations.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="chart-container">
        <div class="chart-title">Disorders by Occupation</div>
        <div class="chart-placeholder">
          <img src="disorderxocupacion.png" alt="Disorders by Occupation">
        </div>
        <p class="chart-description">Certain occupations—especially shift-based or high-stress jobs—have a higher prevalence of sleep-related issues.</p>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="conclusion" id="conclusion">
      <h2 style="color:white;">Conclusion</h2>
      <p>This project reveals significant relationships between lifestyle and sleep. Physical activity improves sleep, while stress and work-related pressure worsen it. Our results serve as a base to promote sleep health programs and guide individuals toward better rest practices using real data.</p>
